+## Product intent
+
+The first-launch tutorial is a short playable pixel-art adventure rather than
+a sequence of isolated button prompts.
+
+The player may move continuously through a wide scrolling course, approach and
+mount the horse, ride it, fight, heal, dismount, traverse hazards, use advanced
+combat actions and collect the final memory. Tutorial instructions appear at
+the relevant location or scripted story moment and fade away while the player
+travels between lessons.
+
+The course remains directed enough to teach systems in a safe order, but each
+lesson provides real movement, spacing and timing instead of advancing after a
+single abstract input.
+
+## Course structure
+
+The playable world spans from `-920` to `1700` tutorial units and contains:
+
+1. free movement in the opening clearing;
+2. approaching and mounting the horse;
+3. riding to an ambush;
+4. a scripted projectile that injures the horse and dismounts the player;
+5. light-attack combat;
+6. the horse returning and a held healing interaction;
+7. remounting and mounted ranged combat;
+8. riding to a marked dismount area;
+9. an actual dodge across a hazard;
+10. heavy, spinning and parry encounters;
+11. a held grapple across a blocking gap;
+12. collecting the final memory.
+
+Forward course gates prevent skipping an unfinished lesson. Backtracking and
+local movement remain available, so the tutorial does not become a slideshow.
+
+## Simultaneous controls
+
+Keyboard/mouse, gamepad and physical handheld controls remain live in parallel:
+
+| Action | Keyboard / mouse | Physical handheld |
+|---|---|---|
+| Move | WASD / arrows | D-Pad |
+| Mount, dismount, collect | E | SELECT |
+| Light attack | J / left click | X |
+| Mounted ranged attack | Q | A |
+| Heal horse | hold F | hold A |
+| Dodge | Space | B |
+| Heavy attack | K / right click | Y |
+| Spin | hold J / left click | hold X |
+| Parry | K / right click at the correct moment | Y |
+| Grapple | hold K / right click | hold Y |
+| Exit | Escape / Back | EXIT |
+
+Contextual input priority is mandatory. The south/A route fires during the
+mounted ranged lesson, heals during the healing lesson and otherwise remains
+the normal interaction route. The same physical control may never be consumed
+by the wrong action owner.
+
+## Action animation contract
+
+Every taught action has a distinct, readable, basic pixel animation:
+
+- **Mount / dismount:** short stepped hop between player and saddle.
+- **Light attack:** wind-up, player lunge, slash bar and enemy hit shake.
+- **Ranged attack:** mounted recoil, muzzle flash, travelling projectile and
+  target impact.
+- **Dodge:** compressed player pose, real displacement and fading trail.
+- **Heavy attack:** larger wind-up, committed lunge, impact block and target
+  squash.
+- **Spin:** stepped player-facing flips with an expanding square ring.
+- **Parry:** braced player pose, square guard flash and projectile rebound.
+- **Grapple:** extending line followed by a visible pull across the gap.
+- **Heal:** kneeling/leaning player pose, horse pulse and rising healing cross.
+- **Horse hit:** stepped shake, collapse pose and red impact cross.
+
+Animations use unscaled time and a deliberately stepped frame cadence. They are
+clear enough to communicate the action without competing with the modern,
+large instruction cards.
+
+## Instruction pacing
+
+The instruction panel is not permanently displayed. It appears:
+
+- when the tutorial boots;
+- when the player reaches the horse or a lesson station;
+- during the three short story beats;
+- when an action requires a hold or timing window;
+- at completion.
+
+Between stations it fades away so the player can see and play the course.
+
+## Non-overlap and clarity
+
+- World, title/progress, transient feedback and instruction panel own separate
+  safe regions.
+- Course decorations remain outside the central interaction lane.
+- The camera follows the player while the Mask clips the wide course.
+- No action effect or decoration may cover instructional text.
+- All generated world sprites remain point-filtered.
+
+## Performance and ownership
+
+- One tutorial owner and one normalized lesson state machine.
+- Gameplay and action presentation are split into partial source files under
+  the same authoritative presenter.
+- Action effect objects are created once and reused; no per-action texture,
+  material or GameObject allocation.
+- Physics is not introduced for the tutorial course.
+- UI transforms and small color/scale changes are the only per-frame work.
+- Runtime-generated pixel textures are disposed with the tutorial page.
+
+## Acceptance
+
+- The player can move freely with keyboard and D-Pad throughout travel phases.
+- The horse can be mounted, ridden and dismounted.
+- No lesson can be skipped by walking through its forward gate.
+- All ten action presentations are visible and match the performed action.
+- The ranged lesson includes recoil, muzzle flash and a moving projectile.
+- The player can complete the course using keyboard/mouse only.
+- The player can complete the course using physical controls only.
+- A mixed-input run can switch routes at any time.
+- Instructions appear contextually rather than every frame.
+- Exit confirmation, clean-install persistence, skip persistence and normal
+  main-menu transition remain correct.
